history.note: Agreed upon at the APL meeting, 2005-11-02 to 2005-11-04.

history.description: SPASE version 0.99.7 Released.
Changed "AcceptableAbbreviation" to "ConventionalAbbreviation" since abbreviations are not supported in the model.
Updated definition of "Magnetotail", etc. to be generic; Added "Earth" examples.
Added all planets and the Moon under "Body".
Added "Near1AU" under Heliosphere; Added "Body" under "Atmosphere-Ionosphere", "Magnetosphere" and "Ground".
Added "WaveForm", "Spectra", etc. under "AnalysisMethod".
Added "AnalysisMethod" under "Field" "Electric" and "Magnetic".
Move Polar Angle under Particle "IndependentVariable".
Drop Speed from Particle "IndependentVariable".
Move Wavelength and Wave Number under Photon "IndependentVariable".
Changed "PhotonContext" and "ParticleContext" to "IndependentVariable".
Added "Description" and "TensorOrder" under "Parameter".
Removed "Provider" and "Manufacture" resources and replaced with ID pointers.
Introduced "PhotonContext" and "ParticleContext" as replacements for "IndependentVariable".
Changed "UpperLatitude" to "HighLatitude" and "Lower" to "Low".
Removed "Ratio" (Numerator and Denominator).
Added "Spherical" and "Cartesian" under "Position".
Removed "Body" and references to it.
Changed "Surface" to "Ground".
Corrected the inclusion of "Atmosphere-Ionosphere" regions into the "Magnetosphere".
SPASE version 0.99.5 Released.
Added "parameter" loosely based on a model proposed by D.A. Roberts.
Included region descriptions from J. King with additions suggested by K. Reardon.
Added "Catalog", "DisplayData" to the top list.
Added document elements to product resources.
Changed data types of "Integer" to "Count" and "Double" to "Numeric".
Clarified some definitions and corrected typographical errors.
history.note: Per J. Thieman and J. Hourcle

history.description: SPASE version 0.99.4 Released.
Added definitions for new elements introduced in the new taxonomy.
Restructured the taxonomy of elements to match the one suggested by D.A. Roberts.
Added definitions supplied by J. Thieman, C. Harvey and T. King; Significant revision of document as suggested by J. Hourcle.
SPASE version 0.99.2 Released.
Corrected "NumericalData" entry under "Product".
SPASE version 0.99.1 Released.
Added "ParticleCorrelator" and "SpacecraftPotentialControl" under "InstrumentType".
Added C. Harvey definition for "Electron Drift".
Removed duplicate entries.

Boundary.definition: Parameters that define a region in space.

Container.definition: A "Container" of other elements including text fields and containers.

DateTime.definition: A value is given in the ISO 8601 recommended primary standard notation: YYYY-MM-DD. where YYYY is the year in the usual Gregorian calendar, MM is the month of the year between 01 (January) and 12 (December), and DD is the day of the month between 01 and 31. It may also have an optional time portion given in the ISO 8601 recommended primary standard notation: HH:MM:SS.sss where HH is the number of complete hours that have passed since midnight (00-24), MM is the number of complete minutes that have passed since the start of the hour (00-59), and SS is the number of complete seconds since the start of the minute (00-60), and sss are milliseconds that have passed since the start of the second (000-999). Time zones are not allowed so all times are in Universal Time. The time portion must follow the date portion with both portions separated by a "T". For example, "2004-07-29" is July 29, 2004 and "2004-07-29T12:30:00" is precisely 12:30 on July 29, 2004.

Duration.definition: A duration of time. The SPASE element "Cadence" is an example of a Duration type SPASE element where cadence refers to the delta T or time between consecutive data points in a time series. A SPASE Duration text field is required to be formatted to comply with the ISO 8601 recommended primary standard notation. If a time duration is less that a day the PTHH:MM:SS.sss format applies where PT are tokens to indicate that the time value is a duration, HH is the number of complete hours, MM is the number of complete minutes that have passed since the start of the hour (00-59), and SS is the number of complete seconds since the start of the minute (00-60), and sss are milliseconds that have passed since the start of the second (000-999). If a time duration s longer than or equal to a day, then the ISO 8601 P format applies where for example P1D, P1M, and P1Y represent time cadences of one day, one month, and one year, respectively. Other examples of SPASE Duration-type elements includes DiagnosisTimeStep, DisplayCadence, Exposure, Per, RelativeStopDate, and TimeStep.

Enumeration.definition: Value is selected from a list of allowed values. The name of list is an additional attribute of the element. Lists may be externally controlled in which case the location of the list is indicated in the textual definition of the element.

FloatSequence.definition: A list of floating point numbers where the order of the values is fixed. A space separates each value. For example, "1.2 3.4 5.6".

Item.definition: An element which is a value for an enumerated list.

Numeric.definition: A fractional number which can be expressed in scientific notation. The string "NaN" represents not-a-number (flag) values and the string "INF" represents an infinitely large value. The value "-INF" represents an infinitely small value.

Sequence.definition: A list of whole number values where the order of the values is fixed. A space separates each value. For example, "1 2 3".

StringSequence.definition: A list of strings where the order of the values is fixed. A space separates each value. For example, "one two three".

Text.definition: A string of alphanumeric characters. A text based "markup" is supported. See the "Text Mark-up" section in specification document for complete details.

Value.definition: A description of the standardized measurement increments in which a value is specified. The description is represented as a mathematical phrase. Units should be represented by widely accepted representation. For example, units should conform to the International System of Units (SI) which is maintained by BIPM (Bureau International des Poids et Mesures (see http://www.bipm.fr/ ) when appropriate or use tokens like "Re" to represent units of the Radius of the Earth. Within a phrase the circumflex (^) is used to indicate a power, a star (*) is used to indicate multiplication and a slash (/) division. When symbols are not separated by a mathematical operator, multiplication is assumed. Symbols for base units and for commonly derived units can be found by accessing links listed in the Bibliography below for the International System of Units (SI) hosted by the Bureau des Poids et Mesures (BIPM).

1P-Halley.definition: 1P/Halley, is a short-period comet visible from Earth every 75 to 79 years. The comet was visited by the Halley Armada comprised of the ESA Giotto, Japanese Suisei and Sekigake, and Soviet Union Vega 1 and Vega 2 spacecraft in 1986.

26P-Grigg-Skjellerup.definition: 26P/Grigg-Skjellerup is a periodic comet. It was visited by the ESA Giotto spacecraft in July 1992.

2DCuts.definition: A set of 2-D arrays that contain the values of physical parameters, i.e., magnetic field vectors, particle densities, temperatures, etc., at the grid points located in a planar slice of a model volume.

3DCubes.definition: A set of 3-D arrays that contain the values of physical parameters, i.e., magnetic field vectors, particle densities, temperatures, etc., at grid points in a model volume.

67P-Churyumov-Gerasimenko.definition: 67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko is a Jupiter-family comet originally from the Kuiper belt. The ESA Rosetta spacecraft rendezvoused with Comet 67P on August 6, 2014 and then orbited the comet from September 10, 2014 to September 30, 2016. Philae, a lander carried by Rosetta, touched down on the comet surface on November 12, 2014.

Absorption.definition: Decrease of radiant energy (relative to the background continuum spectrum).

AccessDirectoryTemplate.definition: Directory hierarchy templates to store the patterns for the data directory structure, using the URI template specification https://github.com/hapi-server/uri-templates/wiki/Specification. This will enable automated search of files matching a time range. For example, the ACE definitive orbit dataset at NASA SPDF has yearly subdirectories for the data files following the naming pattern $Y. See links for access templates in the Bibliography.

AccessFilenameTemplate.definition: Filenaming templates to store the patterns for the data filename structure, using the URI template specification https://github.com/hapi-server/uri-templates/wiki/Specification. This will enable automated search of files matching a time range. For example, the ACE definitive orbit dataset at NASA SPDF has files following the naming pattern "ac_or_def_$Y$m$d_v$v.cdf", where $Y is the year, $m is the month, $d is the day, and $v is the version number. See links for access templates in the Bibliography.

AccessInformation.definition: Attributes which specify how to access a resource, its availability, storage format, etc.

AccessInformationOptional.definition: Attributes of the resource which pertain to how to accessing the resource, availability and storage format. This resource class is an exact copy of the AccessInformation container. However, as its name suggests, AccessInformationOptional is not a required element.

AccessRights.definition: Permissions granted or denied by the host of a product to allow other users to access and use the resource.

AccessURL.definition: Attributes of the method for accessing a resource including a URL, name and description.

ACElectricField.definition: Alternating electric field component of a wave.

Acknowledgement.definition: The individual, group or organization which should be acknowledged when the data are used in or contributes to a presentation or publication.

ACMagneticField.definition: Alternating magnetic field component of a wave.

Active.definition: Exerting an influence or producing a change or effect. An active measurement is one which produces a transmission or excitation as a part of the measurement cycle.

ActiveRegion.definition: A localized, transient volume of the solar atmosphere in which PLAGEs, SUNSPOTS, FACULAe, FLAREs, etc. may be observed.

ActivityIndex.definition: An indication, derived from one or more measurements, of the level of activity of an object or region, such as sunspot number, F10.7 flux, Dst, or the Polar Cap Indices.

Address.definition: Directions for finding some location written on letters or packages that are to be delivered to that location.

AdiabaticInvariant.definition: A property of a physical system usually related to periodic phenomena that remains constant under slowly varying conditions.

Aerosol.definition: A suspension of fine solid or liquid particles in a gas.

Agency.definition: The name of an organization that provides a service or funding for specific projects.

AkasofuEpsilon.definition: A measure of the magnetopause energy flux and an indicator of the solar wind power available for subsequent magnetospheric energization. Defined as: V*B^2*l^2sin(theta/2)^4 where B is the IMF, l is an empirical scaling parameter equal to 7 R<sub>E</sub>, and theta=tan(By/Bz)^-1 the IMF clock angle.

Albedo.definition: The ratio of reflected radiation from the surface to incident radiation upon it.

AlfvenMachNumber.definition: The ratio of the bulk flow speed to the Alfven speed.

AlfvenVelocity.definition: Phase velocity of the Alfven wave. In SI units it is the velocity of the magnetic field divided by the square root of the mass density times the permeability of free space (μ<sub>0</sub>).

AlphaParticle.definition: A positively charged nuclear particle that consists of two protons and two neutrons.

AlternateName.definition: An alternative or shortened name used to refer to a resource. This includes acronyms, expanded names or a synonym for a resource.

Amplitude.definition: The maximum extent of a vibration or oscillation, measured from equilibrium.

Ancillary.definition: A complementary item which can be subordinate, subsidiary, auxiliary, supplementary to the primary item.

Annotation.definition: Information which is explanatory or descriptive which is associated with another resource.

Anomaly.definition: An interval where measurements or observations may be adversely affected.

Antenna.definition: A sensor used to measure electric potential.

AOGCM.definition: Coupled atmosphere-ocean-sea ice global climate models solve the full equations for mass and energy transfer and radiant exchange.

API.definition: An application programming interface (API) is a form of interface that allows applications to access the features or data of an operating system, application, or other service. An API may have a required protocol or set of principles. Some examples of protocols are SOAP, XML-RPC and JSON-RPC. An example of an API with a set of principles is REST.

ApplicationInterface.definition: The type of interface for the application.

ArchiveSpecialist.definition: An individual who is an expert on a collection of resources and may also be knowledgeable of the phenomenon and related physics represented by the resources. This includes librarians, curators, archive scientists and other experts.

Area.definition: Integration over the extent of a planar region, or of the surface of a solid.

Ariel.definition: The fourth largest moon of Uranus.

Array.definition: A sequence of values corresponding to the elements in a rectilinear, n-dimension matrix. Each value can be referenced by a unique index.

ArrivalDirection.definition: An angular measure of the direction from which an energetic particle or photon was incident on a detector. The angles may be measured in any coordinate system.

ASCII.definition: A sequence of characters that adheres to American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) which is a 7-bit character-coding scheme.

Association.definition: Attributes of a relationship a resource has with another resource.

AssociationID.definition: The resource identifier for a resource with which this resource is closely associated.

AssociationType.definition: A characterization of the role or purpose of the resource being described in relationship to the resource with the AssociationID being referenced.

Asteroid.definition: A small extraterrestrial body consisting mostly of rock and metal that is in orbit around the Sun.

Atmosphere.definition: The neutral gases surrounding a body that extends from the surface and is bound to the body by virtue of the gravitational attraction.

Atom.definition: Matter consisting of a nucleus surrounded by electrons which has no net charge.

AtomicNumber.definition: The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom.

AtomicNumberDetected.definition: The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom as determined by a detector.

Aurora.definition: A natural electrical phenomenon characterized by the appearance of streamers of reddish or greenish light in the sky, especially near the northern or southern magnetic pole. The effect is caused by the interaction of charged particles from the sun with atoms in the upper atmosphere. In northern and southern regions, it is respectively called aurora borealis or Northern Lights and aurora australis or Southern Lights.

AuroralRegion.definition: The region in the atmospheric where electrically-charged particles bombarding the upper atmosphere of a planet in the presence of a magnetic field produce an optical phenomenon.

Author.definition: The composer or creator of an artifact. This can include presentations, articles, books, white papers, data products or any similar published work. In SPASE, Author is a Role under Person resource description.

Authors.definition: The individuals or organizations who defined or specified a resource (document, data, images or other types of resources). Separate multiple names with a semicolon. When an author is a person use the "last, first [, middle]" name format. Including a middle name is optional (Since 2.6.1).

Automatic.definition: Determined by the analysis or assessment performed by a program or server.

AutoSpectrum.definition: The Fourier transform of the auto correlation function for physical or empirical observations, which describes the general dependence of the time series data values at one instant on the time series data values at another instant.

Availability.definition: An indication of the method or service which may be used to access the resource.

Average.definition: The statistical mean equal to the sum of a set of values divided by the number of values in the set.

AverageChargeState.definition: A measure of the composite deficit (positive) or excess (negative) of electrons with respect to protons.

AVI.definition: Audio Video Interleave (AVI) a digital format for movies that conforms to the Microsoft Windows Resource Interchange File Format (RIFF).

AwardNumber.definition: The identifying information assigned to the financial support (funding) of a project.

AxisLabel.definition: A short character string (approximately 10 characters, but preferably 6 characters, more only if absolutely required for clarity) which can be used to label a y-axis for a plot or to provide a heading for a data listing.

AzimuthalAngleRange.definition: The range of possible azimuthal angles for a group of energy observations. Default units are degrees.

AzimuthAngle.definition: The angle between the projection into the I-J plane of a position or measured vector and the I-axis of the coordinate system. Mathematically defined as arctan(J/I). This term could be also applied to angles measured in different planes, i.e., the IMF clock angle defined as arctan(|By|/Bz).

BackWall.definition: Back wall of the model domain by which the plasma flow may exit the model.

BandName.definition: A common or provider assigned name for a range of values.

Bandwidth.definition: Integration over the width a frequency band.

Base64.definition: A data encoding scheme whereby binary-encoded data is converted to printable ASCII characters. It is defined as a MIME content transfer encoding for use in Internet e-mail. The only characters used are the upper-case and lower-case Roman alphabet characters (A-z), the numerals (0-9), and the "+" and "/" symbols, with the "=" symbol as a special suffix (padding) code.

Bin.definition: A grouping of observations according to a band or window of a common attribute.

Binary.definition: A direct representation of the bits which may be stored in memory on a computer.

BounceMotion.definition: The second adiabatic invariant is associated with periodic bounce motion of charged particles trapped between two magnetic mirrors on a magnetic field line. The second invariant, termed J, is defined by using the integral J=m ∫ v||*ds where m is the mass of the charged particle, v|| is the particle velocity along the field line, and ds represents elemental arc lengths along the field line. The second adiabatic invariant is conserved as long as changes in the background magnetic field occur at time scales much longer than the bounce time of the charged particles.

BoundaryConditions.definition: Parameters associated to the model boundaries.

BowShockCrossing.definition: A crossing of the boundary between the undisturbed (except for foreshock effects) solar wind and the shocked, decelerated solar wind of the magnetosheath.

Browse.definition: A representation of an image which is suitable to reveal most or all of the details of the image.

BZIP2.definition: An open standard algorithm by Julian Seward using Burrows-Wheeler block sorting and Huffman coding, see http://www.bzip.org/.

Cadence.definition: The nominal or most common time interval between the start of successive measurements.

CadenceMax.definition: The largest time interval between the start of successive measurements.

CadenceMin.definition: The smallest time interval between the start of successive measurements.

CaK.definition: A spectrum with a wavelength of range centered near 393.5 nm. VSO nickname: Ca-K image with range of 391.9 nm to 395.2 nm.

Calibrated.definition: Data wherein sensor outputs have been convolved with instrument response function, often irreversibly, to yield data in physical units. Similar to NASA Level 2.

Callisto.definition: A second largest moon of Jupiter and the third largest moon in the solar system.

Carrington.definition: A coordinate system which is centered at the Sun and is fixed with respect to the synodic rotation rate. The mean synodic value is about 27.2753 days. The Astronomical Almanac gives a value for Carrington longitude of 349.03 deg at 0000 UT on 1 January 1995.

Cartesian.definition: A representation in which a position vector or a measured vector (e.g., field or flow) is specified by its components along the base axes of the coordinate system.

Catalog.definition: A tabular listing of events or observational notes, especially those that have utility in aiding a user in locating data. Catalogs include lists of events, files in a product, and data availability. A Catalog resource is a type of "data product" which is a set of data that is uniformly processed and formatted, from one or more instruments, typically spanning the full duration of the observations of the relevant instrument(s). A data product may consist of a collection of granules of successive time spans, but may be a single high-level entity.

Caveats.definition: Information which may be important in the avoidance of the misuse of the resource, for instance instrument maladies, corruption or contamination.

CDF.definition: Common Data Format (CDF). A binary storage format developed at Goddard Space Flight Center (GSFC).

CEF.definition: Cluster Exchange Format (CEF) is a self-documenting ASCII format designed for the exchange of data. There are two versions of CEF which are not totally compatible.

CEF1.definition: Cluster Exchange Format (CEF), version 1, is a self-documenting ASCII format designed for the exchange of data. The metadata contains information compatible with the ISTP recommendations for CDF.

CEF2.definition: Cluster Exchange Format (CEF), version 2, is a self-documenting ASCII format designed for the exchange of data and introduced for Cluster Active Archive. Compared to version 1, the metadata description of vectors and tensors is different.

CenterElevation.definition: The elevation in the center of a region above a surface (such as sea level or land) of a planet or natural satellite.

CenterLatitude.definition: The latitude in the center of a region in a geographic coordinate system.

CenterLongitude.definition: The longitude in the center of a region in a geographic coordinate system.

CGM.definition: Corrected Geomagnetic - A coordinate system from a spatial point with GEO radial distance and geomagnetic latitude and longitude, follow the epoch-appropriate IGRF/DGRF model field vector through to the point where the field line crosses the geomagnetic dipole equatorial plane. Then trace the dipole magnetic field vector Earthward from that point on the equatorial plane, in the same hemisphere as the original point, until the initial radial distance is reached. Designate the dipole latitude and longitude at that point as the CGM latitude and longitude of the original point, see http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space/cgm/cgmm_des.html.

Channeltron.definition: An instrument that detects electrons, ions, and ultraviolet radiation, according to the principle of a secondary emission multiplier. It is typically used in electron spectroscopy and mass spectrometry.

Characteristic.definition: A quantity which can be easily identified and measured in a given environment.

ChargeExchange.definition: Chemical process involving a charge transfer from an ion (which becomes neutral) to a neutral (which becomes ionized).

ChargeFlux.definition: The number of ionized particles passing through a unit area per unit time, for instance as measured by a Faraday cup.

ChargeState.definition: Charge of a fully or partially stripped ion, in units of the charge of a proton. Charge state of a bare proton is equal to one.

Checksum.definition: A computed value that is dependent upon the contents of a digital data object. Primarily used to check whether errors or alterations have occurred during the transmission or storage of a data object.

ChemicalFormula.definition: Chemical formula representing a population of particle.

ChildEventOf.definition: A descendant or caused by another resource.

Chromosphere.definition: The region of the solar (or stellar) atmosphere above the temperature minimum and below the Transition Region. The solar chromosphere is approximately 400 km to 2100 km above the photosphere, and characterized by temperatures that range from 4500 K to 28000 K.

Circular.definition: Relative to polarization, right-handed circularly polarized light is defined such that the electric field is rotating clockwise as seen by an observer towards whom the wave is moving. Left-handed circularly polarized light is defined such that the electric field is rotating counterclockwise as seen by an observer towards whom the wave is moving. The polarization of magnetohydrodynamic waves is specified with respect to the ambient mean magnetic field. Right-handed polarized waves have a transverse electric field component which turns in a right-handed sense (that of the gyrating electrons) around the magnetic field.

ClassificationMethod.definition: The technique used to determine the characteristics of an object.

CLI.definition: A command-line interface (CLI) is a form of interface where input to an application is provided as lines of text typically within a shell.

CodeLanguage.definition: A formal language, which comprises a set of instructions that produce various kinds of output.

Coherence.definition: The coherence between two signals x(t) and y(t), C<sub>xy</sub>, is a real-valued function. The square of the coherence is defined by using: Cxy^2=|Gxy(f)|^2/Gxx(f)Gyy(f) where Gxy(f) is equal to the cross-spectral density between two time series denoted as x and y, respectively, and Gxx(f) and Gyy(f) are equal to the auto-spectral densities of the same two time series. Values of Cxy^2 always lie in the range between zero and one, 0<=Cxy^2<=1, in accordance with the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality.

CoInvestigator.definition: An individual who is a scientific peer and major participant in an investigation.

Collection.definition: An aggregation of resources, which may encompass collections of one resource type as well as those of mixed types. A collection is described as a group. Its parts may also be separately described. An example is an experiment which uses the data from multiple instruments (or sensors). Another example is a research effort that uses a set of display images of the Sun and Energetic particle data from the corresponding times for the images, and FITS files of AIA images, etc. All the resources that are part of the research effort can be described as a Collection. Yet another example is a coordinated set of time series used for determining an index.

ColorBar.definition: A spectrum or set of colors used to represent data values.

Column.definition: A 2-D measure of a quantity. The column is the area over which the quantity is measured.

Comet.definition: A relatively small extraterrestrial body consisting of a frozen mass that travels around the Sun in a highly elliptical orbit.

Component.definition: Projection of a vector along one of the base axes of a coordinate system.

Confidence.definition: An expression of how certain that a quantity is valid or accurate.

ConfidenceRating.definition: A classification of the certainty of an assertion.

Contact.definition: The person or organization who may be able to provide special assistance or serve as a channel for communication for additional information about a resource.

Contributor.definition: An entity responsible for making contributions to the content of the resource.

Convention.definition: A set of agreed, stipulated, or generally accepted approaches or methods of adopting a standard or implementing an approach.

CoordinateRepresentation.definition: The method or form for specifying a given point or vector in a given coordinate system.

CoordinatesLabel.definition: A string list of the labels of each dimension of the spatial domain.

CoordinateSystem.definition: The specification of the orientation of a set of (typically) orthogonal base axes.

CoordinateSystemName.definition: Identifies the coordinate system in which the position, direction or observation has been expressed.

CoPI.definition: An individual who is peer of a principal investigator and is an administrative and scientific lead for an investigation.

Core.definition: The central or main part of an object or calculated distribution. For example, the part of a distribution of particles at low energies that is a thermal (Maxwellian) population.

Cores.definition: An application processor that is part of a CPU.

Corona.definition: The outermost atmospheric region of the Sun or a star, characterized by ionization temperatures above 10^5 K. The solar corona starts at about 2100 km above the photosphere. There is no generally defined upper limit.

CoronalHole.definition: An extended region of the corona, exceptionally low in density and associated with unipolar photospheric regions. A coronal hole can be an open magnetic field in the corona and (perhaps) inner heliosphere which has a faster than average solar wind outflow velocity. A region of lower than quiet coronal ion densities and electron densities in the corona or a coronal region with lower peak electron temperature than that found under quiet coronal conditions.

CoronalMassEjection.definition: A solar event (CME) that involves a burst of plasma ejected into the interplanetary medium. CMEs may be observed remotely relatively near the Sun or in situ in the interplanetary medium. Note that CMEs are often referred to as Interplanetary CMEs (ICMEs).

Coronograph.definition: An instrument which can image things very close to the Sun by using a disk to block the bright surface of the sun or a star that reveals the faint corona of the Sun or other celestial objects.

CountRate.definition: The number of events per unit time.

Counts.definition: The number of detection events occurring in a detector over the detector accumulation time.

CrossSection.definition: Cross section of the reaction, when the reaction implies the collision of two particles.

CrossSpectrum.definition: The Fourier transform of the cross correlation of two physical or empirical observations.

CSO.definition: Corrected Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Earth where x-axis is anti-sunward and the y-axis points in the orbital velocity direction.

CSV.definition: Comma Separated Value - A data exchange format defined by RFC 4180.

CubesDescription.definition: A description of the configuration of the set of 3-D arrays that contain the values of physical parameters, i.e., magnetic field vectors, particle densities, temperatures, etc., at grid points in a model volume.

Current.definition: It is the scalar quantity giving the net charge (summed over charged particle species) per unit time flowing across a given surface.

CurrentDensity.definition: It is the vector quantity giving the net charge (summed over charged particle species) per unit cross-sectional area per unit time flowing through a given point. Measurements of current density are often provided in terms of the magnetic perturbations (superposed upon a background magnetic field, if present) associated with the current density.

CutsDescription.definition: A description of the configuration of the set of 2-D array points that contain the values of physical parameters, i.e., magnetic field vectors, particle densities, temperatures, etc., at the grid points located in a planar slice of a model volume.

Cylindrical.definition: A coordinate representation of a position vector or measured vector (field or flow) by its k-component, the magnitude of its projection into the i-j plane, and the azimuthal angle of the i-j plane projection.

Data.definition: A collection of organized information, usually the results of experience, observation or experiment, or a set of premises. This may consist of numbers, words, or images, particularly as measurements or observations of a set of variables.

DataExtent.definition: The area of storage in a file system required to store the contents of a resource. By default, the data extent is expressed in bytes.

DataProducer.definition: An individual who generated the resource and is familiar with its provenance.

DataQuality.definition: An ancillary parameter that denotes the standard or degree of accuracy, trustworthiness, or usefulness of another parameter.

Deimos.definition: The smaller and outermost of the two natural satellites of Mars.

DensityProfile.definition: Density profile of the particles in a population.

DeputyPI.definition: An individual who is an administrative or scientific leader for an investigation operating under the supervision of a Principal Investigator.

DerivedFrom.definition: A transformed or altered version of a resource instance.

Description.definition: A narrative explanation with detail appropriate for the item it describes. For example, a description of data resource should include discussions of the main quantities in the resource, possible uses and search terms. A description should also include whether any corrections (i.e., geometry, inertial) have been applied to the resource.

Developer.definition: The developer of a system to imitate a situation or process.

Deviation.definition: The difference between an observed value and the expected value of a quantity.

DiagnosisTimeStep.definition: Time at which a diagnosis is performed and quantity saved.

Differential.definition: A measurement within a narrow range of energy and/or solid angle.

Dimension.definition: The number of items along one axis.

Dione.definition: The fourth largest moon of Saturn.

Direction.definition: The spatial relation between an object and another object, the orientation of the object or the course along which the object points or moves.

Directional.definition: A measurement within a narrow range of solid angle.

DirectionAngle.definition: An enumeration list of angular measures for specifying the direction of an n-dimensional vector within the n-dimensional coordinate system in use or the angular deviation of an n-dimensional vector from an (n-1)-dimensional plane, depending on the application. [Note: DirectionAngle must be used with a sub enumeration term: DirectionAngle.AzimuthAngle; DirectionAngle.ElevationAngle; DirectionAngle.PolarAngle].

DirectionCosine.definition: The cosine of the angle between two vectors usually between a vector and one of the basis axes defining a Cartesian coordinate system. Three angles and thus three direction cosines are required to define a vector direction in a 3-D Euclidean space.

DisplayCadence.definition: The time interval between the successive display elements.

DisplayData.definition: A graphical representation of data wherein the underlying numeric values are not (readily) accessible for analysis. Examples are line plots and spectrograms. A Display Data resource is a type of "data product" which is a set of data that is uniformly processed and formatted, from one or more instruments, typically spanning the full duration of the observations of the relevant instrument(s). A data product may consist of a collection of granules of successive time spans, but may be a single high-level entity.

DisplayOutput.definition: A graphical representation of data wherein the underlying numeric values are not (readily) accessible for analysis. Examples are line plots and spectrograms. A Display Data resource is a type of "data product" which is a set of data that is uniformly processed and formatted, from one or more instruments, typically spanning the full duration of the observations of the relevant instrument(s). A data product may consist of a collection of granules of successive time spans, but may be a single high-level entity.

DisplayType.definition: The general styling or type of plot that is suitable for the variable.

DissociativeRecombination.definition: Chemical process by which an ion is neutralized by capturing an electron, and splits in two new neutral species.

Distribution.definition: Velocity distribution of the particles in a population.

DM.definition: Dipole Meridian - A coordinate system centered at the observation point. The z-axis is parallel to the dipole axis of the Earth, positive northward. x-axis is in the plane defined by the z-axis and the line linking the observation point with the center of the Earth. The y-axis is positive eastward, see http://cdpp.cnes.fr/00428.pdf.

Document.definition: A set of information designed and presented as an individual entity. A document may contain plain or formatted text, in-line graphics, sound, other multimedia data, or hypermedia references. A Document resource is intended for use on digital objects that have no other identifier (e.g., DOI or ISBN).

DocumentType.definition: A characterization of the content, purpose, or style of the document.

DOI.definition: A digital object identifier (DOI) is a unique alphanumeric string assigned by a registration agency (the International DOI Foundation) to identify content and provide a persistent link to its location on the Internet.

DopplerFrequency.definition: Change in the frequency of a propagating wave due to motion of the source, the observer, the reflector, or the propagation medium.

Dopplergram.definition: A map or image depicting the spatial distribution of line-of-sight velocities of the observed object.

DoubleSphere.definition: A dipole antenna of which the active (sensor) elements are small spheres located at the ends of two wires deployed in the equatorial plane, on opposite sides of a spinning spacecraft.

DRegion.definition: The layer of the ionosphere that exists approximately 50 km to 95 km above the surface of the Earth. One of several layers in the ionosphere.

DriftMotion.definition: The third invariant for charged particle motion in a dipolar magnetic field is associated with drift of its guiding center in the equatorial plane. The conserved quantity, J<sub>2</sub>, is equal to qφ where q is the particle charge and φ is the magnetic flux enclosed within the particle drift path.

Dust.definition: Free microscopic particles of solid material.

DustDetector.definition: An instrument which determines the mass and speed of ambient dust particles.

DynamicPressure.definition: Dynamic pressure is a measure of the kinetic energy per unit volume of a fluid. For instance, the solar wind dynamic pressure or ram pressure for a purely proton plasma is equal to m<sub>p</sub> n V<sup>2</sup> where m<sub>p</sub> is the proton mass, n is the proton number density, and V is the solar wind speed.

Earth.definition: The third planet from the Sun in our solar system.

EasternmostLongitude.definition: The longitude furthest to the east in a geographic coordinate system.

ECD.definition: Eccentric Dipole (ECD) coordinate system that aligns with a dipole whose origin and orientation may be different from the physical center and spin axis of the containing body. The IGRF-12 coefficients for 2015 are used to determine the origin for the Earth. The 2015 positions are North dip pole: latitude: 86.29, longitude -160.06. South dip pole latitude: -64.28, longitude: 136.59, North geometric pole latitude: 80.37, longitude: -72.63, South geomagnetic pole latitude: -80.37, longitude: 107.37. ECD is defined in doi:10.1186/s40623-015-0228-9.

ECEF.definition: The Earth-Centered, Earth-Fixed (ECEF) coordinate system has point (0,0,0) defined as the center of mass of the Earth. Its axes are aligned with the International Reference Pole (IRP) and International Reference Meridian (IRM). The x-axis intersects the sphere of the Earth at 0 deg latitude (Equator) and 0 deg longitude (Greenwich). The z-axis points north. The y-axis completes the right-handed coordinate system.

EITWave.definition: A wave in the corona of the Sun that generates shock waves in the solar chromosphere (Moreton Waves). EIT Waves are produced by large solar flare and expand outward at about 1,000 km/s. It usually appears as a slowly moving diffuse arc of brightening in H-alpha, and may travel for several hundred thousand km.

Electric.definition: The physical attribute that exerts an electrical force.

ElectricField.definition: A region of space around a charged particle, or between two voltages within which a force is exerted on charged objects in its vicinity. An electric field is the electric force per unit charge.

Electrohydrodynamic.definition: The study of the motions of ionized particles or molecules and their interactions with electric fields and the surrounding fluid [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrohydrodynamics].

Electromagnetic.definition: Electric and magnetic field variations in time and space that propagate through a medium or a vacuum. The wave propagation direction, electric field vector, and magnetic field vector form an orthogonal triad. Waves in this category are detected by having their field quantities measured.

Electron.definition: An elementary particle that has a negative charge equal to about 1.60218*10^-19 C and a rest mass equal to about 9.10938*10^-31 kg.

ElectronDriftInstrument.definition: An active experiment to measure the electron drift velocity based on sensing the displacement of a weak beam of electrons after one gyration in the ambient magnetic field.

ElectronImpact.definition: Chemical process by which a neutral is ionized thanks to the energy from the impact of an electron.

Electrostatic.definition: Collective longitudinal electric-field and plasma oscillations trapped within a body of plasma.

ElectrostaticAnalyser.definition: An instrument which uses charged plates to analyze the mass, charge and kinetic energies of charged particles which enter the instrument.

Element.definition: A component or individual unit of a multiple value quantity such as an array or vector.

ElementBoundary.definition: Parameters associated to the model boundaries.

Elevation.definition: The distance in meters above (positive) or below (negative) the zero-elevation defined by the World Geodetic System reference frame (WGS84).

ElevationAngle.definition: The angle between the position or measured vector and the I-J plane of the coordinate system. Mathematically defined as arctan(K/sqrt(I^2+J^2)).

Email.definition: The electronic address at which the individual may be contacted expressed in the form "local-part@domain".

Emissivity.definition: The energy emitted spontaneously per unit bandwidth (typically frequency) per unit time per unit mass of source. Emissivity is usually integrated over all directions/solid angles.

Empirical.definition: Information obtained through observation, experiment, or experience.

Enceladus.definition: The sixth largest moon of Saturn. It is currently endogenously active. The smallest known body in the Solar System that is geologically active today.

EncodedParameter.definition: A variable that uses successive bits to encode, this is bitwise encode, a set of conditions by using a composited multi-bit numeric value. A common example is a bitwise encoded flag that denotes whether various possible errors that may affect a particular measurement. For example, a bit value equal to zero may indicate the absence of a particular error condition while a value equal to one would indicate the possibility that the associated datum should be ignored or used with caution due to the same error categorization.

EnergeticParticleInstrument.definition: An instrument that measures fluxes of charged particles as a function of time, direction of motion, mass, charge and/or species.

EnergeticParticles.definition: Pieces of matter that are moving very fast. Energetic particles include protons, electrons, neutrons, neutrinos, the nuclei of atoms, and other sub-atomic particles.

EnergeticSolarParticleEvent.definition: An enhancement of interplanetary fluxes of energetic ions accelerated by interplanetary shocks and/or solar flares.

Energy.definition: The capacity for doing work as measured by the capability of doing work (potential energy) or the conversion of this capability to motion (kinetic energy).

EnergyDensity.definition: The amount of energy per unit volume.

EnergyFlux.definition: The amount of energy passing through a unit area in a unit time.

EnergyPerCharge.definition: The kinetic energy, E, per unit net charge, q, that is E/q, for an electron or an ionized atom, molecule, or dust particle.

EnergyRange.definition: The minimum and maximum energy values of the particles represented by a given physical parameter description.

ENP.definition: ENP (also called PEN) - The P-axis points northward, perpendicular to orbital plane. For an orbit with zero inclination, the P-axis is parallel to spin axis of the Earth. The E-axis is perpendicular to the P and N directions and points earthward. The N-axis is perpendicular to P and E and is positive eastward.

Entropy.definition: A function of thermodynamic quantity, such as temperature, pressure, or composition, that is a measure of the energy that is not available for work during a thermodynamic process. It is often interpreted as the degree of disorder or randomness in the system.

Ephemeris.definition: The spatial coordinates of a body as a function of time. When used as an Instrument Type it represents the process or methods used to generate spatial coordinates.

EPNTAP.definition: Europlanet (EPN) Table Access Protocol (TAP) is a framework, which is using TAP with the EPNcore metadata dictionary. The EPNcore metadata dictionary defines the core components that are necessary to perform data discovery in the Solar System related science fields, see https://github.com/ivoa-std/EPNTAP.

EquatorialRegion.definition: A region centered on the equator and limited in latitude by approximately 23 deg north and south of the equator.

EquivalentWidth.definition: The spectral width of a total absorption line having the amount of absorbed radiant energy being equivalent to that in an observed absorption line.

ERegion.definition: A layer of ionized gas occurring at 90 km to 150 km above the ground. One of several layers in the ionosphere. Also called the Kennelly-Heaviside layer.

Europa.definition: The sixth closest round moon of Jupiter.

Event.definition: An action or observation which occurs at a point in time.

Excel.definition: A Microsoft spreadsheet format used to hold a variety of data in tables which can include calculations.

ExecutionEnvironment.definition: An execution platform for software which includes an operating system and necessary hardware.

Experiment.definition: A collection of components which are designed to make coordinated observations of a phenomenon or object. Projects and missions may refer to an "experiment" by other names such as a "suite".

ExpirationDate.definition: The date and time when a resource is no longer available. If the Expiration Date is specified then it indicates that resource should not be made available after that time. However, this is only advisory and in practice a resource description should be unpublished to eliminate access to a resource.

Exposure.definition: The time interval over which an individual measurement is taken.

ExposureMax.definition: The largest interval over which an individual measurement is taken.

ExposureMin.definition: The smallest time interval over which an individual measurement is taken.

Extension.definition: A container of other metadata which is not part of the SPASE data model. The contents of this element are defined by individual usage. The organization and content are constrained by the implementation. For example, in an XML representation of the SPASE metadata the content must conform to the XML specifications.

ExtremeUltraviolet.definition: A spectrum with a wavelength range of 10 nm to 125 nm. VSO nickname: EUV image with a range of 10 nm to 125 nm.

FaradayCup.definition: An instrument consisting of an electrode from which electrical current is measured while a charged particle beam (electrons or ions) impinges on it. Used to determine energy spectrum and sometimes ion composition of the impinging particles.

FarUltraviolet.definition: A spectrum with a wavelength range of 122 nm to 200 nm. VSO nickname: FUV image with a range of 122 nm to 200 nm.

FaxNumber.definition: The symbols and numerals required to send a facsimile (FAX) to an individual by telephone. The string may contain punctuation marks such as dash "-" or dot "." to separate fields within the string.

Feature.definition: A prominent or distinctive characteristic that occurs at a location or persists over a period of time.

Field.definition: The space around a radiating body within which its electromagnetic attributes can exert force on another similar body that is not in direct contact.

FieldAligned.definition: The component of a quantity which is oriented in the same direction of a field.

FieldBoundary.definition: Parameters associated with the field boundaries of the model.

FieldDimension.definition: Number of field dimensions in the model domain.

FieldModel.definition: Field model imposed in the model run.

FieldQuantity.definition: The physical attribute of the field.

FieldValue.definition: A string list of the values of the input parameter.

File.definition: Access to a file containing the data.

FillValue.definition: A value that indicates that a quantity is undefined.

Film.definition: An image recording medium on which usually a negative analog image is registered. A positive analog image can be recovered or reproduced from film, which is usually made of flexible materials for ease of storage and transportation.

Fit.definition: Values that make a model agree with the data.

FITS.definition: Flexible Image Transport System (FITS) is a digital format primarily designed to store scientific data sets consisting of multi-dimensional arrays (1-D spectra, 2-D images or 3-D data cubes) and 2-D tables containing rows and columns of data.

FlowSpeed.definition: The magnitude of the flow velocity.

FlowVelocity.definition: The mean velocity of all particles in the flow, also referred to as bulk velocity or average flow velocity.

Fluence.definition: The time integral of a flux. A fluence is a not a measurement of flux per unit time.

FluxFeedback.definition: A search coil whose bandwidth and signal/noise ratio are increased by the application of negative feedback at the sensor (flux) level by driving a collocated coil with a signal from the preamplifier.

ForbushDecrease.definition: A rapid decrease in the observed galactic cosmic ray intensity following the passage of an outwardly convecting interplanetary magnetic field disturbance, such as those associated with large CMEs, that sweep some galactic cosmic rays away from Earth.

Format.definition: The file format specification. The value is selected from a list of accepted names for known, well documented formats.

FormerPI.definition: An individual who had served as the administrative and scientific lead for an investigation, but no longer assumes that role.

FourierTransformSpectrograph.definition: An instrument that determines the spectra of a radiative source, using time domain measurements and a Fourier transform.

FRegion.definition: A layer that contains ionized gases at a height of around 150-800 km above sea level, placing it in the thermosphere. the F region has the highest concentration of free electrons and ions anywhere in the atmosphere. It may be thought of as comprising two layers, the F1 layer and F2 layer. One of several layers in the ionosphere. Also known as the Appleton layer.

Frequency.definition: The number of occurrences of a repeating event per unit time.

FrequencyRange.definition: The range of possible values for the observed frequency.

FrequencyToGyrofrequencyRatio.definition: The ratio of the characteristic frequency of a medium to gyrofrequency of a particle.

FrontWall.definition: Front wall of the model domain by which the plasma flow may be injected.

Funding.definition: The source of financial support (funding) for the resource.

GammaRays.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 0.00001 nm to 0.001 nm.

Ganymede.definition: The biggest moon of Jupiter and in the solar system.

GCM.definition: A Global Circulation Model (GCM) is a type of climate model, which employs mathematical equations to simulate the motion of a planetary atmosphere or ocean.

GEI.definition: GEI Geocentric Equatorial Inertial - A coordinate system where the z-axis is along spin axis of the Earth, positive northward. The x-axis points towards the first point of Aries (from the Earth towards the Sun at the vernal equinox), see Russell, 1971. When the x-axis is the direction of the mean vernal equinox of J2000, the coordinate system is also called GCI. Then the z-axis is also defined as being normal to the mean Earth equator of J2000.

GeigerMuellerTube.definition: An instrument which measures density of ionizing radiation based on interactions with a gas.

GeneralContact.definition: An individual who can provide information on a range of subjects or who can direct you to a domain expert.

GEO.definition: Geographic - geocentric corotating - A coordinate system where the z-axis is along spin axis of the Earth, positive northward. The x-axis lies in Greenwich meridian, positive towards Greenwich, see Russell, 1971.

GeomagneticStorm.definition: A magnetospheric disturbance typically defined by variations in the horizontal component of the surface magnetic field on the Earth. The variation typically starts with a field enhancement associated with a solar wind pressure pulse and continues with a field depression associated with an enhancement of the diamagnetic magnetospheric ring current.

GeometricFactor.definition: A measure of the gathering power of a particle detector. The geometric factor can be used to correct particle measurements by accounting for the fact that only a fraction of the source particles is able to gain entry through the aperture of a detector. For an isotopic source distribution, the geometric factor corresponds to the solid angle subtended by the aperture. In practice, determination of the geometric factor requires numerical modeling and depends on detector design and the characteristics of the source.

GIF.definition: Graphic Interchange Format (GIF) first introduced in 1987 by CompuServe. GIF uses LZW compression and images are limited to 256 colors.

Git.definition: Git is a version control system for tracking changes in any set of files. It is known for its speed, data integrity, and support for distributed, non-linear workflows.

GPHIO.definition: Kronian Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Saturn where the x-axis is anti-sunward and the y-axis points in the orbital velocity direction.

Granule.definition: An accessible portion of another resource. A Granule may be composed of one or more physical pieces (files) which are considered inseparable. For example, a data storage format that maintains metadata and binary data in separate, but tightly coupled files. Granules should not be used to group files that have simple relationships or which are associated through a parent resource. For example, each file containing a time interval data for a Numerical Data resource would each be considered a Granule. The ParentID of a Granule resource must be a NumericalData resource. The attributes of a Granule supersede the corresponding attributes in the NumericalData resource.

GridCellSize.definition: A string list of the cell sizes in each dimension.

Group.definition: An assemblage of values that a certain relation or common characteristic.

GSE.definition: Geocentric Solar Ecliptic - A coordinate system where the x-axis is from Earth to Sun. The z-axis is normal to the ecliptic, positive northward, see Russell, 1971.

GSEQ.definition: Geocentric Solar Equatorial - A coordinate system where the x-axis is from Earth to Sun. The y-axis is parallel to solar equatorial plane. The z-axis is positive northward, see Russell, 1971.

GSM.definition: Geocentric Solar Magnetospheric - A coordinate system where the x-axis is from Earth to Sun, z-axis is northward in a plane containing the x-axis and the geomagnetic dipole axis, see Russell, 1971.

GUI.definition: A graphical user interface (GUI) is a form of user interface that allows users to interact with an application through graphical icons, forms and other elements with both a keyboard and a pointing device.

Gyrofrequency.definition: The number of gyrations around a magnetic guiding center (field line) a charged particle makes per unit time due to the Lorentz force.

GZIP.definition: An open standard algorithm distributed by GHU based on LZ77 and Huffman coding, see http://www.gnu.org/software/gzip/gzip.html or http://www.gzip.org/.

HAE.definition: Heliocentric Aries Ecliptic - A coordinate system where the z-axis is normal to the ecliptic plane, positive northward. The x-axis is positive towards the first point of Aries (from Earth to Sun at vernal equinox). Same as SE below, see Hapgood, 1992.

Halo.definition: The part of an object or distribution surrounding some central body or distribution. For example, the particles above the core energies that show enhancements above the thermal population. Typically, a "power law tail" shows a break from the core Maxwellian at a particular energy.

Halpha.definition: A spectrum with a wavelength range centered at 656.3 nm. VSO nickname: H-alpha image with a spectrum range of 655.8 nm to 656.8 nm.

HAPI.definition: A Heliophysics Application Programmer Interface (HAPI) specification compliant access point.

Hardcopy.definition: A permanent reproduction, or copy in the form of a physical object, of any media suitable for direct use by a person.

HardXRays.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 0.001 nm to 0.1 nm and an energy range of 12 keV to 120 keV.

HashFunction.definition: A function or algorithm that converts a digital data object into a hash value. Typically, the hash value is small and concise when compared to the digital data object.

HashValue.definition: The value calculated by a hash function, e.g., the message digest of a digital data object.

HCC.definition: Heliocentric Cartesian - A 3-D orthonormal coordinate system that is primarily intended to specify with two dimensions a point on the solar disk. The z-axis points toward the observer. The y-axis lies in the plane defined by the solar spin vector and the z-axis is positive northward. The x-axis is perpendicular to the y-axis and z-axis, positive toward solar west. Standard representation for this system is based on (x,y) position of the point of interest expressed either as physical distances or as fractions of the solar disk radius.

HCR.definition: Heliocentric Radial - A 3-D orthonormal coordinate system that is primarily intended to specify with two dimensions a point on the solar disk. The z-axis points toward the observer. The y-axis lies in the plane defined by the solar spin vector and the z-axis, positive northward. The x-axis is perpendicular to the y-axis and z-axis, positive toward solar west. Standard representation for this system is based on distance rho from the z-axis (sqrt(x**2+y**2)) and the phase angle psi measured counterclockwise from the positive y-axis (arctan(-y/x)) of the point of interest.

He10830.definition: A spectrum with a wavelength range centered at 1082.9 nm. VSO nickname: an He 10830 image with a range of 1082.5 nm to 1083.3 nm.

He304.definition: A spectrum centered around the resonance line of ionized helium at 304 Angstrom (30.4 nm).

HeatFlux.definition: Flow of thermal energy through a gas or plasma typically computed as third moment of a distribution function.

HEE.definition: Heliocentric Earth Ecliptic - A coordinate system where the z-axis is normal to the ecliptic plane, positive northward. The x-axis points from Sun to Earth, see Hapgood, 1992.

HEEQ.definition: Heliocentric Earth Equatorial - A coordinate system where the z-axis is normal to the solar equatorial plane, positive northward. The x-axis is generally Earthward in the plane defined by the z-axis and the Sun-Earth direction, see Hapgood, 1992.

Heliosheath.definition: The region extending radially outward from the heliospheric termination shock and in which the decelerated solar wind plasma is still significant.

Heliosphere.definition: The solar atmosphere extending roughly from the outer corona to the edge of the solar plasma at the heliopause separating primarily solar plasma from interstellar plasma.

HERTN.definition: Helio-Ecliptic Radial Tangential Normal coordinate system. Typically centered at a spacecraft. The x-axis (radial) is set as the primary-axis, and is defined as the axis pointing from the spacecraft to the Sun. The z-axis (tangential) is set as the secondary-axis, and is defined as that portion of the ecliptic rotational axis which is perpendicular to the primary-axis. The y-axis (Normal) is defined as Z cross X.

HG.definition: Heliographic - A heliocentric rotating coordinate system where the z-axis is normal to the solar equatorial plane, positive northward. The x-axis and y-axis rotate with a period of 25.38 days. The zero longitude (x-axis) is defined as the longitude that passed through the ascending node of the solar equator on the ecliptic plane on 1 January, 1854 at 12 UT, see http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space/helios/coor_des.html.

HGI.definition: Heliographic Inertial - A heliocentric coordinate system where the z-axis is normal to the solar equatorial plane, positive northward. The x-axis is along the intersection line between solar equatorial and ecliptic planes. The x-axis was positive at SE longitude of 74.367 deg on January 1, 1900. (See SE below.) See http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space/helios/coor_des.html.

HGRTN.definition: Heliocentric Radial Tangential Normal coordinate system (also known as RTN). Typically centered at a spacecraft. Used for IMF and plasma V vectors. The x-axis (radial) is set as the primary-axis, and is defined as the axis pointing from the spacecraft to the Sun. The z-axis (tangential) is set as the secondary-axis, and is defined as that portion of the solar North rotational axis which is perpendicular to the primary-axis. The y-axis (normal) is defined as Z cross X.

High.definition: The largest value within a range of possible values.

Horizontal.definition: Parallel to or in the plane of the horizon or a base line.

HostContact.definition: An individual who can provide specific information with regard the hosting of a resource or supporting software.

Housekeeping.definition: Parameters that indicate the status or health state of instruments or monitoring devices as measured in physical units such as that for current, voltage, or temperature. Housekeeping data can be analyzed to determine whether instruments are working correctly and the knowledge of their values may be used to avoid errors or even device failures.

HPC.definition: Helioprojective Cartesian=A 3-D orthonormal (left-handed) coordinate system that is primarily intended to specify with two dimensions a point on the solar disk. The z-axis points from the observer to the center of the solar disk. The y-axis lies in the plane defined by the solar spin vector and the z-axis, positive northward. The x-axis is perpendicular to the y-axis and z-axis, positive toward solar west. Given as the distance between the observer and the center of the solar disk, the standard representation of an (x,y) point on the solar disk is latitude (arctan(y/d)) and longitude (arctan (x/d)) of the point of interest.

HPR.definition: Helioprojective Radial - A 3-D orthonormal (left-handed) coordinate system that is primarily intended to specify with two dimensions a point on the solar disk. The z-axis points from the observer to the center of the solar disk. The y-axis lies in the plane defined by the solar spin vector and the z-axis, positive northward. The x-axis is perpendicular to the y-axis and z-axis, positive toward solar west. Given as the distance between the observer and the center of the solar disk, the standard representation for this system of an (x,y) point on the solar disk is latitude angle theta (arctan(sqrt(x**2+y**2)/d))) or equivalent declination parameter delta (theta-90 deg) and the phase angle psi as measured counterclockwise from the positive y-axis (psi=arctan(-y/x)) of the point of interest.

HSM.definition: Heliospheric Solar Magnetospheric - A coordinate system where the x-axis is from Earth to Sun, z-axis is northward in a plane containing the x-axis and the geomagnetic dipole axis.

HTML.definition: A text file containing structured information represented in the Hypertext Mark-up Language (HTML), see http://www.w3.org/MarkUp/.

Hybrid.definition: A numerical scheme modeling ions as particles and electrons as a fluid.

Hydrodynamic.definition: Periodic or quasi-periodic oscillations of fluid quantities.

I.definition: Projection of a vector along the first named axis of a coordinate system. Typically, the x-axis, but could be the R-axis for an RTN coordinate system.

Iapetus.definition: The third largest moon of Saturn and the eleventh largest in the Solar System.

IDFS.definition: Instrument Data File Set (IDFS) is a set of files written in a prescribed format which contain data, timing data, and metadata. IDFS was developed at Southwest Research Institute (SwRI).

IDL.definition: Interactive Data Language (IDL) save set. IDL is a proprietary format.

IJ.definition: A measure of the length of a position or measured vector projected into the I-J (typically X-Y) plane of the coordinate system.

IK.definition: A measure of the length of a position or measured vector projected into the I-K (typically X-Z) plane of the coordinate system.

Image.definition: A 2-D representation of data with values at each element of the array related to an intensity or a color.

ImageIntensity.definition: Measurements of the 2-D distribution of the intensity of photons from some region or object such as the Sun or the polar auroral regions, can be in any wavelength band, and polarized, etc.

Imager.definition: An instrument which samples the radiation from an area at one or more spectral ranges emitted or reflected by an object.

ImageURL.definition: A URL to graphic, image or movie.

ImaginaryPart.definition: Any number z can in general be represented by its complex form with z=a+ib where i, which is defined as the square root of -1, signifies the imaginary component of the number z. The coefficient b is called the imaginary part of the complex number z.

ImagingSpectrometer.definition: An instrument which is a multispectral scanner with a very large number of channels (typically from 64 channels up to 256 channels) with very narrow bandwidths.

IMFClockAngle.definition: The clockwise angle of the direction of interplanetary magnetic field (IMF) measured in the plane of the body pole perpendicular to the line between the body and the Sun.

Index.definition: The location of an item in an array or vector. An index can be multivalued to represent the location in a multi-dimensional object. The index of the first item is "1". A value of "0" is a wild card for all elements at the location in an array. A value of "-1" is a reference to the dimension at the location in the array. A "-1" is used when describing the attributes of the dimension, whereas "0" or a positive integer is used to describe attributes of individual elements.

Inferred.definition: Determined by the analysis of other information or resources.

InformationURL.definition: Attributes of the method of acquiring additional information.

Infrared.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 760 nm to 10^6 nm.

Inner.definition: The region of the heliosphere extending radially outward from the solar coronal base to just inside 1 AU.

InputField.definition: Parameters associated to a field imposed in the model.

InputLabel.definition: A string list of the labels of each dimension of the input parameter.

InputParameter.definition: A container of information regarding an input parameter of the model run.

InputPopulation.definition: A container element that specifies the characteristics of a particle population used as input to a model.

InputProcess.definition: Parameters associated to a chemical process happening in the model.

InputProperty.definition: A container of attributes regarding an input property of an application.

InputResourceID.definition: The resource identifier for a resource which was used to generate this resource.

InputTableURL.definition: A URL to a table containing input parameters.

Inspection.definition: Determined by the analysis or assessment performed by a person.

Installer.definition: A piece of software that installs a program or package on a system.

Instrument.definition: A device that makes measurements used to characterize a physical phenomenon, or a family of like devices.

InstrumentGroupID.definition: The identifier of an Instrument resource which the referring resource is a member of.

InstrumentID.definition: The identifier of an Instrument resource.

InstrumentLead.definition: An individual who is the designated leader of an instrument or instrument package.

InstrumentMode.definition: An indication of a state (mode) in which the instrument is operating. How a mode influences the interpretation and representation of data is described in instrument related documentation.

InstrumentScientist.definition: A scientist associated with a science instrument team with special familiarity and expertise on specific aspects of the design and operations of the instrument and the responsibility of ensuring the measurement capabilities of the instrument.

InstrumentStatus.definition: A quantity directly related to the operation or function of an instrument.

InstrumentType.definition: A characterization of an integrated collection of software and hardware containing one or more sensors and associated controls used to produce data on an environment.

Integral.definition: A flux measurement in a broad range of energy and solid angle.

Intensity.definition: The measurement of radiant or wave energy per unit detector area per unit bandwidth per unit solid angle per unit time.

Interferometer.definition: An instrument to study the properties of two or more waves from the pattern of interference created by their superposition.

Interior.definition: The region inside the body which is not visible from outside the body.

InterplanetaryCoronalMassEjection.definition: An Interplanetary Coronal Mass Ejection (ICME) is a Coronal Mass Ejection (CME) observed in the solar wind far away from the Sun.

InterplanetaryShock.definition: A shock propagating generally anti-sunward through the slower solar wind, often seen in front of CME-associated plasma clouds.

Interstellar.definition: The region between stars outside of any stellar heliopause.

InvestigationName.definition: The name given to the contract or engagement which enabled the data to be produced. Each investigation is associated with a Principal Investigator or Guest Investigator who was responsible for the original proposal. For single principal investigator missions each major subsystem having its own identified Team Leader may also be classed as an Investigation for the purposes of data archiving.

Io.definition: The innermost of the four round moons of the planet Jupiter.

Ion.definition: An atom that has acquired a net electric charge by gaining or losing one or more electrons (Note: Z>2).

IonChamber.definition: A device in which the collected electrical charge from ionization in a gas-filled cavity is taken to be the proportion to some parameter (e.g., dose or exposure) of radiation field.

IonComposition.definition: In situ measurements of the relative flux or density of electrically charged particles in the space environment. May give simple fluxes, but full distribution functions are sometimes measured.

IonDrift.definition: A device which measures the current produced by the displacement of ambient ions on a grid, thereby allowing the determination of the ion trajectory and velocity.

IonGauge.definition: A device which measures low-pressure or vacuum neutral gas with pressures ranging from 10^-3 Torr to 10^-10 Torr. An ion gauge is an electronic amplifying vacuum tube consisting of three electrodes inside an evacuated glass envelope, with the filament being the cathode.

Ionosphere.definition: The charged or ionized gases surrounding a body that are nominally bound to the body by virtue of the gravitational attraction.

Irradiance.definition: A radiometric term for the power of electromagnetic radiation at a surface, per unit area. Irradiance is used when the electromagnetic radiation is incident on the surface. Irradiance data may be reported in any units (i.e., counts/s) due to, for example, being at a particular wavelength, or to being a not fully calibrated relative measurement.

J.definition: Projection of a vector along the second named axis of a coordinate system. Typically, the y-axis, but could be the T-axis for an RTN coordinate system.

J2000.definition: An astronomical coordinate system which uses the mean equator and equinox of Julian date 2451545.0 TT (Terrestrial Time), or January 1, 2000, noon TT to define a celestial reference frame.

JK.definition: A measure of the length of a position or measured vector projected into the J-K (typically Y-Z) plane of the coordinate system.

JPEG.definition: A binary format for still images defined by the Joint Photographic Experts Group.

JSM.definition: Jovian Solar Magnetospheric - A coordinate system related to Jupiter where the x-axis is from Jupiter to Sun, z-axis is northward in a plane containing the x-axis and the Jovian dipole axis.

JSO.definition: Jovian Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Jupiter where x-axis is anti-sunward and the y-axis points in the orbital velocity direction.

JSON.definition: JavaScript Object Notation - A lightweight data-interchange format.

Jupiter.definition: The fifth planet from the Sun in our solar system.

K.definition: Projection of a vector along the third named axis of a coordinate system. Typically, the z-axis, but could be the N-axis for an RTN coordinate system.

K7699.definition: A spectrum with a wavelength range centered at 769.9 nm. VSO nickname: K-7699 dopplergram with a range of 769.8 nm to 770.0 nm.

Keyword.definition: A word or phrase that is relevant to the resource but does not exist in other documentary information.

KSM.definition: Kronian Solar Magnetospheric - A coordinate system related to Saturn where the x-axis is anti-sunward, z-axis is northward in a plane containing the x-axis and the Kronian dipole axis.

KSO.definition: Kronian Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Saturn where x-axis is anti-sunward and the y-axis points in the orbital velocity direction.

LandingPageURL.definition: A Uniform Resource Locator (URL) to a page that provides a way to access the resource. A landing page should contain a full bibliographic citation so that a human can tell they have arrived at the correct resource, and additional information about the resource that might not be easily retrievable from the resource itself.

LangmuirProbe.definition: A monopole antenna associated with an instrument. The instrument applies a potential to the antenna which is swept to determine the voltage/current characteristic. This provides information about the plasma surrounding the probe and spacecraft.

Language.definition: The two-character indicator of language selected from the ISO 639-1 codes for the representation of names of languages.

Latitude.definition: The angular distance north (positive) or south (negative) from the equator, measured along the meridian passing through the point.

Layout.definition: The structured arrangement of items in a collection.

LBHBand.definition: Lyman-Birge-Hopfield band in the far ultraviolet range with wavelength range of 140 nm to 170 nm.

LGM.definition: Local Geomagnetic - A coordinate system used mainly for Earth surface or near-Earth surface magnetic field data. The x-axis northward from observation point in a geographic meridian. The z-axis downward towards center of the Earth. In this system, the total horizontal component, H, is equal to sqrt(Bx^2+By^2) and declination angle, D is equal to arctan(By/Bx).

Lidar.definition: Lidar (Light Detection and Ranging) is a class of instruments that uses laser light to study atmospheric properties from the ground up to the top of the atmosphere. Such instruments have been used to study atmospheric gases, aerosols, clouds, and temperature.

LikelihoodRating.definition: The probability that something is true or possible.

Linear.definition: Polarization where the E-field vector is confined to a given plane.

LineDepth.definition: The measure of the amount of absorption below the continuum (depth) in a particular wavelength or frequency in an absorption spectrum.

LineOfSight.definition: The line of sight is the line that connects the observer with the observed object. This expression is often used with measurements of Doppler velocity and magnetic field in magnetograms, where only the component of the vector field directed along the line of sight is measured.

Lines.definition: A set of 1-D arrays that contain the values of physical parameters, i.e., magnetic field vectors, particle densities, temperatures, etc., at the grid points along a line though a model volume. For instance, the points of the line may correspond to the trajectory of a spacecraft through model space.

Listing.definition: A listing of files either through FTP or HTTP.

LocalGeographic.definition: A coordinate system used mainly for Earth surface or near-Earth surface magnetic field or other vector measurements. The X-axis points northward from observation point in a geographic meridian in the horizontal plane. The Y-axis points eastward from observation point in a geographic latitude in the horizontal plane. The Z-axis points downward towards center of the Earth.

LocalGeomagnetic.definition: A coordinate system used mainly for Earth surface or near-Earth surface magnetic field data. The H-axis points northward toward the north magnetic pole from observation point in a geomagnetic meridian in the horizontal plane. The D-axis points eastward from observation point in a geomagnetic latitude in the horizontal plane. The Z-axis points downward towards center of the Earth.

Location.definition: A position in space definable by a regional referencing system and geographic coordinates.

LogScale.definition: Intervals which are spaced proportionally to the logarithms of the values being represented.

Longitude.definition: The angular distance measured west (negative) or east (positive) from a north-south line called the Prime Meridian.

LongWire.definition: A dipole antenna constructed by two active sensing elements that are wires deployed in the equatorial plane on opposite sides of a spinning spacecraft. The, wire length is usually several times the spacecraft diameter.

Low.definition: The smallest value within a range of possible values.
